- Is this village really unaffected by the Cullings? [if Variables.get_var("unaffected") == false]
	Shopkeeper: Sure is. Not a single death, ever since they started occurring all those years ago. [do Variables.mod_var("questions", 1)][do Variables.set_var("unaffected", true)]
	Shopkeeper: The sky does turn red in the morning, heralding a Culling day, and we've had people die just outside our walls. 
	Shopkeeper: Gruesome, horrific way to go. Glad I've only witnessed it this one time.
	Shopkeeper: But inside, nothing. Not once. The Goddess cares for and protects us.
	- How is this possible?
		Shopkeeper: You'll have to see it to believe it. Perhaps, if you're a doubter now, those doubts will vanish then. 
		Shopkeeper: The Cullings are our Goddess's work. 
		Shopkeeper: It is punishment for humanity's sins over the years. And a way to cleanse the Earth and start anew.
		Shopkeeper: Sounds brutal, I know. But we, as a species, have been ruthless ourselves to this planet, our own home, driving it to a point where it was nearly uninhabitable anymore. 
		Shopkeeper: Something had to be done. 
		- I've seen countless people die horrible deaths. I can tell you, it is not worth it. 
			Shopkeeper: Who are we to say, at the end of the day? It's how things are now and we have to adjust to it, either way. => questions
		- We had it coming. Hopefully some good comes out of it. 
			Shopkeeper: Time will tell. Either way, it's how things are now and we have to adjust to it. => questions
	- Could it be that She's the one causing them, then?
		Shopkeeper: She sure is. It's a well known fact around here. 
		Shopkeeper: It is punishment for humanity's sins over the years. And a way to cleanse the Earth and start anew.
		Shopkeeper: Sounds brutal, I know. But we ourselves, as a species, have been ruthless to this planet, our own home, driving it to a point where it was nearly uninhabitable anymore. 
