~ tutorial
Shopkeeper: First things first. I'll neeed to explain how the Cullings really work. 
Shopkeeper: Besides infecting people with spots of corruption that quite literally suck the life out of them, the Cullings also yield a residual substance that attaches itself to worldly, man-made items. 
Shopkeeper: While the manner in which said corruption targets and attaches itself to people or items is seemingly random, there's surely a logic and a purpose to it, known only to the Goddess Herself.
Shopkeeper: Whenever the sky turns red in the morning - a harbinger of the Cullings, as you well know - some people die, and some items become corrupted. 
Shopkeeper: While the goodwill of our Goddess has fortunately kept us safe from the former, we have sadly not been unaffected by the latter. 
Shopkeeper: Interesting thing is, the residual substance that attaches itself to objects is invisible to the human eye. 
Shopkeeper: Anyone can see the spots of corruption that cause people to die gruesome deaths. But only a few of us, who have had the good fortune of being blessed by the Goddess with Her Gift of sight, can see the spots of corruption that infect our everyday objects. 
Shopkeeper: Though most people can't see said spots, their side effects can be felt by anyone. Using, interacting with or looking at an infected object can cause madness, ilness, and the appearance of violent urges.
Shopkeeper: Sometimes, people can even hear the object talking to them, inciting them to violence. No wonder they go mad. 
Shopkeeper: Luckily, you and I can rid the items of their evil. And that's why people send them to us. 
Shopkeeper: All we gotta do is, quite literally, rip the evil spots off like a bandaid using our little hands and fingers. 
Shopkeeper: There. Look down and to your left. There's an infected object on the table.
Shopkeeper: Pick it up and put it down in front of you, for now. 
#tutorial: look down, move objects, quarantine zone
Shopkeeper: Now pick it up again and give it a proper look. Rotate it around, try to really focus on it. Make sure to put it back down after a few seconds.
#tutorial: rotate, focus mode
Shopkeeper: Feels weird, eh? Focus on it long enough and you might just die. No, really, I'm not kidding.
Shopkeeper: You need constant breaks in our line of work. Whenever it starts to hurt, or when you feel like you might be losing it, put the item down. Take a moment to breathe.
Shopkeeper: You'll feel fine again soon enough. And then you're back to peeling. 
Shopkeeper: Speaking of, let's try peeling the evil off this one. Pick it back up, focus on it, and run your fingers over those weird looking spots. Then peel. 
Shopkeeper: Remember, take breaks if you feel the need. 
#tutorial: peeling, managing your health
Shopkeeper: Well done. Put it in the basket, to your right. / No worries, no one gets it right the first time. Try again. / Almost. You've got it this time. 
#tutorial: done zone
Shopkeeper: Now let's try another one. 
Shopkeeper: This one has been infected longer. Its evil is more frenetic. Some of its spots will move around erratically, while some others will move inward when observed for too long, infecting it forever.
Shopkeeper: Make sure to target those first. And remember, put it down from time to time. Better it stay that way than you become infected yourself. Items can be burned, but you can't come back if the evil gets its hooks in you. 
Shopkeeper: Give it a go. 
#tutorial: different stickers
Shopkeeper: Great job. You're a natural, eh? / Yep, this one's trickier. Give it another go. / Still better than I was at first. No harm done. Again. / There we go. In the basket it goes. 
Shopkeeper: That's it. Our day consists of doing this over and over again, taking short breaks whenever we feel the need, and longer ones once every two or three objects. Safer that way. Easy to get lost in this kind of work. 
Shopkeeper: Like I said, make sure you don't get too absorbed in it. Look around, talk to me or to Micah or to whoever finds themselves in this sorry place, peer out the window, anything. Balance is key. 
Shopkeeper: You can keep practicing, if you so wish. These items are from old batches, anyway. Their owners are long dead, mostly.
Shopkeeper: When you're ready, I'll introduce you to my daughter, Sarah, and to our beloved delivery boy, Micah. He's one of the Elders' messengers, collecting infected items from around the village and bringing 'em to us. 
=> END

